{{nihongo|'''''Yakuman'''''|役満}} is a 1989 [[mahjong]] [[video game]] developed by [[Intelligent Systems]] and published by [[Nintendo]] for its handheld [[Game Boy]] as one of the Japanese launch titles. It is the first entry in a series of first-party [[Japanese mahjong]] games on Nintendo systems, with sequels on the [[Famicom]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://w.atwiki.jp/famicomall/pages/435.html|title=役満天国|website=「FCのゲーム制覇しましょ」まとめ|date=17 November 2008 }}</ref> [[Game Boy Advance]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/n08/ayaj/index.html|title=どこでも対局 役満アドバンス|website=www.nintendo.co.jp}}</ref> [[Nintendo DS|DS]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/ds/amjj/index.html|title=役満ＤＳ|website=www.nintendo.co.jp}}</ref> [[Wii]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/wii/wiiware/waqj/index.html|title=役満Ｗｉｉ 井出洋介の健康麻将|website=www.nintendo.co.jp}}</ref> [[Wii U]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/titles/20010000007586|title=役満 鳳凰 &#124; Wii U &#124; 任天堂|website=任天堂ホームページ}}</ref> and [[3DS]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/3ds/dl/aghj/|title=役満 鳳凰|website=www.nintendo.co.jp}}</ref>

==Summary==
[[File:YakumanScreenshotGameBoy.png|160px|left|thumb|A sample game of ''Yakuman'' being played]]
As one of the four original Game Boy games available for the Japanese launch of that system on April 21, 1989, ''Yakuman'' was released alongside ''[[Alleyway (video game)|Alleyway]]'', ''[[Super Mario Land]]'', and ''[[Baseball (1983 video game)|Baseball]]''. It is the only game of the four that was never released outside Japan. It has both a single player mode and a two player versus mode.<ref name="mobygames">[http://www.mobygames.com/game/gameboy/yakuman ''Yakuman''] at [[MobyGames]]</ref> 

Japanese mahjong is a four player [[tile-based game]] where the goal is to take points from other players by drawing and discarding tiles until a winning hand is made. A "Yakuman" is a class of rare and valuable winning hands that can be composed of different combinations of tiles than normal hands.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ofb.net/~whuang/ugcs/gp/mahjong/mahjong.html.utf8|title=Japanese Mahjong Scoring|date=August 16, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816025533/http://www.ofb.net/~whuang/ugcs/gp/mahjong/mahjong.html.utf8|archive-date=2016-08-16}}</ref> The mahjong in ''Yakuman'' is a two player variation of this game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/n02/dmg/mjj/|script-title=ja:役満|lang=ja|website=www.nintendo.co.jp}}</ref>

==Legacy==
The Yakuman Player as seen on the cover art appears as a collectible sticker in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Brawl]]''.{{citation needed|date=January 2024}} He appears again, as a spirit, in ''[[Super Smash Bros. Ultimate]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hobbyconsolas.com/guias-trucos/super-smash-bros-ultimate/todos-espiritus-super-smash-bros-ultimate-347581 |title=Todos los espíritus en Super Smash Bros Ultimate |work=Hobby Consolas |last=Hernández |first=David |date=December 21, 2018 |accessdate=January 26, 2024}}</ref>

